    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Japan, What's on the Plate Is Culture</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carole LaRocca letter says enlightened societies have recognized value of living whales, and Japan has no right to ignore worldwide opinion; adds that US also has no right to claim superiority on animal rights when billions of animals are slaughtered to satisfy American food tastes (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>By arguing that ''it's part of our culture'' and therefore acceptable to slaughter whales, Japan is saying the rest of the world is wrong for banning whale hunts (front page, Aug. 10).</p>
        <p>Enlightened societies have recognized the value of living whales, and Japan has no right to ignore worldwide opinion. Any infractions of existing laws should be met with harsh sanctions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>By arguing that ''it's part of our culture'' and therefore acceptable to slaughter whales, Japan is saying the rest of the world is wrong for banning whale hunts (front page, Aug. 10).</p>
        <p>Enlightened societies have recognized the value of living whales, and Japan has no right to ignore worldwide opinion. Any infractions of existing laws should be met with harsh sanctions.</p>
        <p>But the United States doesn't have the right to lord it over any other country when it comes to animal rights. Billions of animals are slaughtered in this country every year to satisfy our food tastes. A genuine respect for all animals, and protection for them, is desperately needed.</p>
        <p>CAROLE LA ROCCA  Las Vegas, Aug. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
